erbert Baker. It culminates with an analysis of their mutual infatuation with T. E. Lawrence - Lawrence of Arabia - who represented all their dreams for the future British Empire but whose ultimate paralysis of creative imagination exposed the fatal flaw in their psycho-political project. This transdisciplinary study will interest not only scholars of imperialism and the history of ideas but general readers fascinated by bygone ideas of exotic adventure and colonial rule.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aBritish Empire.  aEdward Elgar.  aEdwardian era.  aHerbert Baker.  aIndia.  aJohn Buchan.  aJoseph Conrad.  aLawrence of Arabia: imperial romance.  aRider Haggard.  aRudyard Kipling.  aSigmund Freud.  aThe Loathly Opposite.  aVictorian era.  aforbidden pleasures.  aimaginative literature.  aimperial power.  aimperialism.  apsychoanalytic theory.1 aEtherington, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152610607040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526106070423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526106070/original  a978-3-11-128281-7  Manchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packageb2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles